<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 6.1, Inner Product, Length, and Orthogonality</title>

  <ul marker="">

    <!-- Problem 1 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; Fill in the blanks.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            The distance between the vector
            <m>\vec{u} = \begin{pmatrix}2 \\ 3\end{pmatrix}</m>
            and the line spanned by
            <m>\vec{w} = \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 0\end{pmatrix}</m>
            is __________________.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>W</m> is the plane spanned by the vectors
            <m>\vec{u} = \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 1 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}</m>
            and
            <m>\vec{v} = \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 0 \\ -1\end{pmatrix}</m>,
            a basis of <m>W^\perp</m> is given by
            <m>\vec{w} = \begin{pmatrix} &amp; \\ &amp; \\ &amp; \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If
            <m>
              V = \left\{\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^3 \,\middle|\, x_1 + x_2 = x_3 \right\},
            </m>
            then <m>\dim V =</m> _______
            and <m>\dim V^\perp =</m> _______.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 2 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; <m>W</m> is the set of all vectors of the form
        <m>
        \begin{pmatrix}
          x \\ y \\ x + y
        \end{pmatrix}.
        </m>
      Which of the vectors below are in <m>W^\perp</m>?</p>
      <p>
        <me>
        \vec{u} =
        \begin{pmatrix}8 \\ -5 \\ 8\end{pmatrix},
        \quad
        \vec{v} =
        \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 1 \\ -1\end{pmatrix},
        \quad
        \vec{w} =
        \begin{pmatrix}3 \\ 3 \\ -3\end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 3 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; Indicate whether the statements are true or false.</p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>\vec{x} \in \mathrm{Null}(A)</m>, then <m>\vec{x}</m> is orthogonal
            to the rows of matrix <m>A</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>\vec{u}</m> and <m>\vec{v}</m> are non‑zero orthogonal vectors,
            then they are linearly independent.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

  </ul>
</handout>